[This is the 1st report of Ross River virus infections in Western Australia this year (2013). Ross River virus (RRV) infections in Western Australia increased significantly in 2012. There were 1570 cases in the 2011-2012 transmission season. RRV is a zoonotic alphavirus transmitted by a wide range of mosquitoes including _Aedes_ and _Culex_ species, and although not fatal, causes acute polyarthritis in humans. A candidate RRV vaccine has been tested in humans. The adjuvanted, inactivated whole-virus Vero cell-derived RRV vaccine is highly immunogenic in RRV-naive adults and well tolerated at all dose levels. Since this vaccine is not commercially available, avoidance of mosquito bites, as indicated in the report above, is the only preventive measure available currently.

Reference:
Aichinger G, Ehrlich HJ, Aaskov JG, Fritsch S, Thomasser C, Draxler W, Wolzt M, MÃ¼ller M, Pinl F, Van Damme P, Hens A, Levy J, Portsmouth D, Holzer G, Kistner O, Kreil TR, Barrett PN. Safety and immunogenicity of an inactivated whole virus Vero cell-derived Ross River virus vaccine: a randomized trial. 2011. Vaccine 29(50):9376-84.

